{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's most doubt-saturated couplet**, drawn from his *Diwan*, captures metaphysical perplexity in confronting one's own reflection and the impossibility of multiplicity in the divine or self:  \n\n> You grow perplexed yourself when you behold your mirror's view;  \n> If there were one or two more like you here, how could it be?[^1]\n\nThis exemplifies Ghalib's hallmark skepticism, where existence itself poses unresolvable riddles, blending romantic self-doubt with theological questioning (e.g., echoing Wahdat al-Wujud's oneness paradox).[^2]\n\n**Iqbal's most conviction-saturated verse**, from *Shikwa* in *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, pulses with unyielding *khudi*-infused certainty in Muslim historical agency and divine favor, boldly cataloging triumphs as proof of unbreakable faith:  \n\n> You tell us then, who was it that tore out Khyber’s mighty door?  \n> Who was it that laid Caesar’s city flat upon the floor?  \n> Who smashed the man-made idols of the gods that men adore?  \n> And who was it that cut to shreds the armies of the war?  \n> Who was it that extinguished Zoroaster’s sacred fire?  \n> And who revived the memory of God, our one desire?[^3]\n\nHere, Iqbal's *khudi* (selfhood) manifests as collective self-affirmation: the ummah as history's vanguard, demanding recognition from God Himself—pure conviction, no quarter for hesitation.[^4]\n\n**Could either have penned the other's line on a difficult day?** Unlikely. Ghalib's essence is perpetual ambiguity (\"riddles in the air\");[^5] conviction would feel alien, even in despair—he thrives on the unsolvable. Iqbal's *khudi* steels against weakness; doubt would undermine his prophetic timbre, though a dark day might yield *Shikwa*-like complaint (bold, not bewildered). Their voices are antithetical: Ghalib questions to revel in mystery; Iqbal asserts to conquer it. The corpus offers no crossover evidence.[^6]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [p-1d6472](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/47-gayi-woh-baat-ke-ho-guftugu-to-kyun-kar-ho/translation/#p-1d6472).  \n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [Chapter 44](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/44-gar-khamoshi-se-faida-ikhfa-e-haal-hai/translation/).  \n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [p-ec4443](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-ec4443).  \n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [Chapter 20](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/). Note: *Khudi* appears transliterated across Iqbal's works (e.g., snippets in Part 1 Ch. 18), fueling this self-exalting ethos, though English renders it as emphatic \"we\" or soul-force.  \n[^5]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [p-710e03](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/44-gar-khamoshi-se-faida-ikhfa-e-haal-hai/translation/#p-710e03).  \n[^6]: No related chapters via TF-IDF link Ghalib's doubt directly to Iqbal's resolve; searches for \"khudi\"/\"self\" + conviction yield philosophy mismatches elsewhere in corpus.",
